NECO Method 1: Multilayer Perceptron with Backpropagation¶

Neural Network Creation¶

In [20]:
class BananaQualityNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_sizes, output_size):# 3 parameters are set for this netowork which are the input size,
        # hidden neuron numbers and output size.
        super(BananaQualityNN, self).__init__() 
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_sizes[0], bias=True)# This is the first  hidden layer, which also includes a bias term.
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(hidden_sizes[0], hidden_sizes[1], bias=True)# This is the second hidden layer, which is connected to the first 
        # hidden layer, and also includes a bias term.
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(hidden_sizes[1], output_size, bias=True)# This is the output layer which is connected to the hidden layers
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()# This is the ReLU activation function for the network.
        
    def forward(self, x):# Forward propagation of the network.
        x = self.fc1(x)# Input is passed to the 1st hidden layer.
        x = self.relu(x)# Relu activation function is applied.
        x = self.fc2(x)# Input is passed to the 2nd hidden layer from the 1st.
        x = self.relu(x)# Relu activation function is applied again.
        output = self.fc3(x)# The result is then passed onto the 3rd hidden layer which is intended as an ouput layer.
        return output
    
    def fit_training(self, train_input_data, train_targets, val_input_data, val_targets, learning_rate, epochs, momentum, weight_decay, patience):
        # This line of code, is the one that is used for training and validation of the model on the dataset.
        # train_input_data: The features of the training dataset. This is the data that the model will learn from
        # train_targets: The target labels corresponding to `train_input_data`. These are the true values that the model aims to predict during training.
        # val_input_data: The features of the validation dataset. This data is used to evaluate the model's performance during training
        # val_targets: The target labels for the validation dataset. These are used to validate the accuracy of the model's predictions against unseen data during the training process.
        # learning_rates: The learning rate of the model. 
        # epochs: This parameter specifies how many times the algorithm will work through the training dataset.
        # momentum: A parameter that helps accelerate gradients vectors in the right directions, thus leading to faster converging. 
        # weight_decay: A regularization parameter used to prevent overfitting by reducing large weights.
        # patience: The number of epochs to wait for improvement on the validation set before early stopping.
        criterion = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss() # The loss function, which is basically a measure between the difference of the model's predictions
        # and the actual target data.
        optimizer = optim.Adam(self.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, weight_decay=weight_decay)# It is a critical component that adjusts the weights and biases of the network.
        highest_val_loss = float('inf')# Tracking the lowest validation loss during training.
        early_stopping = 0# Initialises the early stopping count to 0.
        train_losses = []# Training loss for each epoch.
        val_losses = []# Validation loss for each epoch.
        
        for epoch in range(epochs):# Loop over the dataset multiple times.
            self.train()# Initialise training.
            predictions = self(train_input_data)# Forward pass: Compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model.
            loss = criterion(predictions, train_targets.view(-1,1))# Calculate the loss between predicted and target values.
            optimizer.zero_grad()# Zero the parameter gradients to prevent accumulation.
            loss.backward()# Backward pass: compute gradient of the loss with respect to model parameters
            optimizer.step()# Update the model parameters.
            train_losses.append(loss.item())# Record training loss.
            
            self.eval()# Setting the model into evaluation mode.
            with torch.no_grad():# Disabling the gradient calculation to save on computational power.
                val_predictions = self(val_input_data)# Compute predictions on the validation set.
                val_loss = criterion(val_predictions, val_targets.view(-1, 1))# Calculation of validation set.
                val_losses.append(val_loss.item())# Record the validation set.
            if val_loss.item() < highest_val_loss:# Check if current validation loss is lower than the best so far.
                highest_val_loss = val_loss.item()# Update the best (lowest) validation loss.
                early_stopping = 0# Reset early stopping counter.
            else:
                early_stopping += 1# Increment early stopping counter if no improvement.
                
            if early_stopping > patience:# Check if early stopping criteria are met.
                print(f'Early Stopping at {epoch}')
                break# Exit the training loop.
                
        return train_losses, val_losses# Return lists of training and validation losses.
        
    def predictions(self, X):
        self.eval()# Switch the model to evaluation mode.
        with torch.no_grad():# Prevent calculation of gradient.
            predictions = self(X)# Compute the model's predictions.
            final_predictions = torch.sigmoid(predictions)# Apply the sigmoid function.
            return (final_predictions >= 0.5).int()# Convert the probabilities to binary (1 or 0).

# https://www.kaggle.com/code/vitorgamalemos/multilayer-perceptron-from-scratch

Parameters and Hyperparameters to be Tested¶

In [21]:
input_size = 7# Number of features in the dataset used as input to the model.
learning_rates = [0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1]# Range of learning rates to experiment with for optimal convergence.
hidden_layer_sizes = [[10, 5], [20, 10], [64, 32], [128, 64]]# Different configurations of neurons in hidden layers to test model complexity.
momentum = 0.6# Momentum value for the optimizer to accelerate gradients in the right direction.
weight_decay = 0.0001# Regularization parameter to reduce overfitting by reducing large weights.
patience = 10# Number of epochs with no improvement on validation loss before early stopping is triggered.
epochs = 1000# Maximum number of training epochs, with early stopping potentially ending training sooner.
In [22]:
optimal_accuracy = 0# Stores the highest accuracy achieved across different hyperparameter settings.
optimal_hyperparameters = {}# Dictionary to store the hyperparameters of the model with the best accuracy.
optimal_losses = {}# Dictionary to store the training and validation losses of the model with the best accuracy.
In [23]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
total_training_time = 0# Initialises total training time.

for lr in learning_rates:# Iterate over each learning rate.
    for hs in hidden_layer_sizes:# Iterate over each hidden layer size.
        start_time = time.time()# Record the start time for training.
        model = BananaQualityNN(input_size=input_size, hidden_sizes=hs, output_size=1)# Initialise the model with current hyperparameters.
        training_losses, validation_losses = model.fit_training(X_train_tensor, Y_train_tensor, X_val_tensor,
                                                                Y_val_tensor,lr, epochs, 
                                                                momentum, weight_decay, patience)
        # Train the model and obtain training and validation losses.
        end_time = time.time()# Record end time for training.
        training_time = end_time - start_time# Calculation of training time.
        training_time = round(training_time,1)# Round up total training time to 1dp.
        total_training_time += training_time# Accumulate total training time.
        val_predictions = model.predictions(X_val_tensor)
        val_accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_val_tensor.numpy(), val_predictions.numpy())
        # Generate predictions on validation set and calculate accuracy.
        print(f"No. of Epochs: {len(training_losses)-1}, Learning Rate: {lr}, Hidden Neuron Size: {hs}, "
              f"Accuracy: {val_accuracy}, Training Time (s): {training_time:.2f}\n")# Print the details for current hyperparameter orientation.
        
        if val_accuracy > optimal_accuracy:
            optimal_accuracy = val_accuracy# Updated the highest recorded accuracy.
            optimal_speed = training_time# Record the training time corresponding to this optimal accuracy.
            optimal_hyperparameters = {'learning_rates': lr, 'hidden_sizes': hs, 'epochs': len(training_losses)-1, 'Training Time (s)': optimal_speed}
            optimal_losses = {'training_losses': training_losses, 'validation_losses': validation_losses}
            # Storing the optimal learning rates, hidden layer sizes, epochs, training time, training losses and validation losses.
print("\nBest Parameters:", optimal_hyperparameters)
print("Best Accuracy:", round(optimal_accuracy, 3))
print('Total Training Time (s) (for all hyperparameter combinations):', round(total_training_time, 1))
# Display the best hyperparameters, the corresponding accuracy, and the total training time for all combinations.
# https://www.kaggle.com/code/vitorgamalemos/multilayer-perceptron-from-scratch

Losses Histogram¶

In [30]:
training_losses = np.array(training_losses)# Converting the training_losses list to a numpy array.
validation_losses = np.array(validation_losses)# Converting the validation_losses to a numpy array.

def freedman_diaconis(data, returnas="width"):# The Freedman-Diaconis method is a statistical rule used to determine 
    #the optimal bin width for histograms. 
    IQR = np.percentile(data, 75) - np.percentile(data, 25)# Calculating the interquartile range.
    N = len(data)# Number of data points.
    bw = (2 * IQR) / np.power(N, 1/3)# Calculating the bin width (bin width formula).
    if returnas == "width":
        return bw# Returning the bin width.
    return int((np.max(data) - np.min(data)) / bw)# Returning the number of bins based on the range of data and bin width.

# Calculating the bin width and number of bins for the training and validation losses, using the Freedman-Diaconis rule.
bin_width_train = freedman_diaconis(training_losses, returnas="width")
bin_width_val = freedman_diaconis(validation_losses, returnas="width")
bins_train = freedman_diaconis(training_losses, returnas="bins")
bins_val = freedman_diaconis(validation_losses, returnas="bins")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))# Setting the size for the plot.
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)# Setting the size for the subplot.
plt.hist(training_losses, bins=bins_train, color='blue', alpha=0.7, label='Training Loss')
plt.xlabel('Loss Value')# x-axis label name.
plt.ylabel('Frequency')# y-axis label name.
plt.title('Histogram of Training Losses')# Setting the title for the subplot
plt.legend()# Displaying the legend for the subplot.

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)# Setting the size for the subplot.
plt.hist(validation_losses, bins=bins_val, color='green', alpha=0.7, label='Validation Loss')
plt.xlabel('Loss Value')# x-axis label name.
plt.ylabel('Frequency')# y-axis label name.
plt.title('Histogram of Validation Losses')# Setting the title for the subplot.
plt.legend()# Displaying the legend for the subplot.

plt.tight_layout()# Tight layout for the subplots to be close together.
plt.show()# Displaying the plot.

# https://medium.com/@maxmarkovvision/optimal-number-of-bins-for-histograms-3d7c48086fde
# https://numpy.org/devdocs/reference/generated/numpy.histogram_bin_edges.html
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33458566/how-to-choose-bins-in-matplotlib-histogram

from sklearn.svm import SVC# Importing the Support Vector Classifier from scikit-learn package.

C_values = [0.01,0.1,1,10]# Defining the list for C values parameters.
Gamma_values = [0.01,0.1,1,10]# Defining the lists for Gamma values parameters.
optimal_val_accuracy = 0# Storing the highest accuracy obtained.
optimal_SVM = None# Storing the SVM model with the highest validation accuracy.
Optimal_Parameters = {'C': None, 'gamma': None, 'kernel': None}# Dictionary to store the best parameters.
# https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.svm.SVC.html

Training of the model, and validation for Optimal Hyperparameters¶

In [33]:
total_start_time = time.time()# Starting the timer for the process.

for C in C_values:# Iterating over each C value in the loop.
    for kernel in ['linear', 'rbf']:
        if kernel == 'linear':# Handling the linear kernel.
            start_time = time.time()# Starting the timer for this case.
            SVM_model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C)# Initializing the SVM model with linear kernel.
            SVM_model.fit(X_train_tensor, Y_train_tensor)# Fit the model on the training data.
            end_time = time.time()# Ending the timer for this case.
            validation_accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_val_tensor, SVM_model.predict(X_val_tensor))
            # Evaluating the model on the validation set.
            print(f'Validation Accuracy with C={C}, kernel={kernel}: {validation_accuracy}')
            # Printing the validation accuracy for the given parameters.
            print(f'Training Time with C={C}, kernel={kernel}: {(end_time - start_time)/60:.2f} mins\n')
            # Printing the training time for the given parameters.
            # Updating the optimal parameters if the current model outperforms previous ones.
            if validation_accuracy > optimal_val_accuracy:
                optimal_val_accuracy = validation_accuracy
                optimal_SVM = SVM_model
                Optimal_Parameters = {'C': C, 'kernel': kernel}
                
        else:# Handling of the rbf kernel case.
            for gamma in Gamma_values:
                start_time = time.time()# Starting the timer for this case.
                SVM_model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C, gamma=gamma)# Initializing the SVM model with rbf kernel.
                SVM_model.fit(X_train_tensor, Y_train_tensor)# Fit the model on the training data.
                end_time = time.time()# Ending the timer for this case.
                validation_accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_val_tensor, SVM_model.predict(X_val_tensor))
                # Evaluating the model on the validation data.
                print(f'Validation Accuracy with C={C}, kernel={kernel}, gamma={gamma}: {validation_accuracy}')
                # Printing the validation accuracy for the given parameters.
                print(f'Training Time with C={C}, kernel={kernel}, gamma={gamma}: {(end_time - start_time)/60:.2f} mins\n')
                # Printing the training time for the given parameters.
                # Updating the optimal parameters if the current model outperforms previous ones.
                if validation_accuracy > optimal_val_accuracy:
                    optimal_val_accuracy = validation_accuracy
                    optimal_SVM = SVM_model
                    Optimal_Parameters = {'C': C, 'gamma': gamma, 'kernel': kernel}
                
print('-'*100)
print("Best Parameters for Validation Set:", Optimal_Parameters)# Printing the best parameters found during the grid search.
total_end_time = time.time()
print('-'*100)
print("Total Training Time: {:.2f} mins".format((total_end_time - total_start_time) / 60))
# Printing the total training time for all configurations.
